{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"710a20d2-910c-4536-934b-4db24e6b4c9a","content":"PID 12345 isn't running on this machine, but here's exactly how to diagnose and configure dumps on your target system:\n\n## 1. Determine the Runtime\n\n```bash\n# If this returns matches → CoreCLR. No matches → NativeAOT.\ngrep -c 'libcoreclr\\.so' /proc/12345/maps\n```\n\nAlternatively:\n\n```bash\n# NativeAOT binaries are fully self-contained single files with no coreclr dependency\nldd $(readlink /proc/12345/exe) | grep -i coreclr\n```\n\n## 2. Configure Crash Dumps\n\n### If CoreCLR\n\nSet environment variables (e.g. in your systemd unit or shell):\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4          # 4 = Full heap dump (Triage=1, Mini=2, Heap=3, Full=4)\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/var/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\n```\n\nAlso ensure the dump directory exists and the OS core pattern doesn't interfere:\n\n```bash\nsudo mkdir -p /var/dumps && sudo chmod 1777 /var/dumps\n# Optional: set kernel core pattern as fallback\necho '/var/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\n### If NativeAOT\n\nNativeAOT **does not** use the `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` variables — it relies entirely on the **OS kernel core dump** mechanism:\n\n```bash\n# Set core pattern\necho '/var/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\nulimit -c unlimited\nsudo mkdir -p /var/dumps && sudo chmod 1777 /var/dumps\n```\n\nIf your system uses **systemd-coredump** (common on modern distros):\n\n```bash\n# Check if active\ncoredumpctl list 2>/dev/null && echo \"systemd-coredump is active\"\n# Dumps are stored in /var/lib/systemd/coredump/ by default\n# Extract with: coredumpctl dump <PID> -o /var/dumps/coredump.dmp\n```\n\n## 3. For a systemd Service (Persistent Config)\n\n```ini\n# /etc/systemd/system/myapp.service.d/dumps.conf\n[Service]\nLimitCORE=infinity\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1       # CoreCLR only\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4         # CoreCLR only\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/var/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\n```\n\nThen `sudo systemctl daemon-reload && sudo systemctl restart myapp`.\n\n**TL;DR**: Run the `grep` command from step 1 on your target machine. If it's CoreCLR, use the `DOTNET_Dbg*` env vars. If it's NativeAOT, configure kernel core dumps via `/proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b36240f0-eda5-42f4-b35b-a5f2541c92cd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process doesn't exist on this machine (PID 12345 is fictional). Let me give the user the diagnostic commands and configuration guidance instead.","outputTokens":837,"requestId":"6084:2E6B36:1162619:15CA6C1:69FFE4FF"},"id":"a978be9a-ddfd-4d92-a7e5-49e8ddb42cbb","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:54:27.456Z","parentId":"f08ac8cf-6681-4bcc-8da2-7c71205676c2"}
